<p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">At MyGet, we live and breath a culture of componentization, and we are very happy to see package authors adopting and sharing these practices within their organizations. One of these practices is the usage of NuGet's&nbsp;</span><a href="http://docs.nuget.org/create/creating-localized-packages" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.42857; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">localized NuGet packages</a><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">&nbsp;feature.&nbsp;</span><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">The adoption of localized satellite packages is a good indicator of package author maturity. Using a better practice should be rewarding and free of friction. One of our Dear Users provided us with great feedback on how he leveraged MyGet to release localized packages by <a href="http://docs.myget.org/docs/reference/package-sources#Scenario_-_Pushing_a_package_upstream" target="_blank">pushing them upstream</a>. However, some unnecessary friction was involved, which had to be removed.</span></p><p><span style="color: inherit; font-family: inherit; font-size: 36px; line-height: 1.1;">Localized NuGet Packages</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">As a NuGet package author, you can provide a localized experience for your libraries</span><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">. The NuGet client has supported the creation of localized satellite packages</span><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">&nbsp;</span><a href="http://docs.nuget.org/Release-Notes/NuGet-1.8#Satellite-Packages-for-Localized-Resources" target="_blank" style="line-height: 1.42857; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">since version 1.8</a><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">.</span></p><p>For those unfamiliar with the concept, here's a basic package graph demonstrating the idea:</p><p><span style="font-weight: bold;">My.Framework.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></p><p></p><ul><li>Meta package, installing My.Framework and all localized satellite packages</li><li>Depends on: all satellite packages (<span style="font-style: italic;">My.Framework.Core.nl, My.Framework.Core.fr, My.Framework.Core.el, ...</span>)</li></ul><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">My.Framework.Core.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></div><div><ul><li>Package containing an actual framework library (e.g. in <span style="font-style: italic;">lib/net45/My.Framework.Core.dll</span>)</li><li>No dependencies for the sake of the demo (your libraries most likely have dependencies :))</li></ul><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">My.Framework.Core.nl.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></div></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">My.Framework.Core.fr.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></div><div><span style="font-weight: bold;">My.Framework.Core.el.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></div><div><ul><li>3 localized satellite packages for the My.Framework.Core package</li><li>Depends on the actual framework package being localized: <span style="font-style: italic;">My.Framework.Core.1.0.0-alpha0001.nupkg</span></li><li>Only contains localization resources (e.g. <span style="font-style: italic;">lib/net45/nl/My.Framework.Core.resources.dll</span>, <span style="font-style: italic;">lib/net45/nl/My.Framework.Core.xml</span>)</li></ul><div>Or visualized in a graph, here's the dependency tree:</div></div><div><br></div><div><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 550px;"><br></div><p></p><p>To facilitate discovery of these satellite packages, we added a convenient <span style="font-weight: bold;">Localization</span>&nbsp;tab on the package details page if localized satellite packages are detected.</p><p><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 550px;"><br></p><h1>Releasing localized NuGet packages</h1><p>Ideally, releasing a package that has localized satellite packages from MyGet to another feed, should be a click of a button away, publishing the entire package-set at once. Optionally, one might also want to adjust the prerelease tag and release notes of this package set, either per package individually, or for all at once.</p><p><span style="font-weight: bold;">The <span style="font-style: italic;">Push Upstream </span>feature (also <a href="http://docs.myget.org/docs/reference/package-sources#Scenario_-_Pushing_a_package_upstream" target="_blank">check our docs</a>) has been upgraded to now also detect package dependencies and localized satellite packages!</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">This means that, as in the above sample scenario, you can now publish the entire localized package-set in one go by pushing the <span style="font-style: italic;">My.Framework</span>&nbsp;meta package upstream.</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;"><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 550px;"><br></span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">In addition, you can also edit (or simply remove!) the prerelease tag and/or release notes for each package individually, <span style="font-weight: bold;">or for all of them at once!</span></span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">Simply click the edit button <img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 50px;">&nbsp;next to one of the packages, modify the fields, and click the water-drop icon <img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 28px;">&nbsp;to apply the changes to all other packages in the dialog.</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;"><img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 550px;"><br></span></p><p><span style="line-height: 20px;">Of course, you can still exclude individual packages from this list if you want to by clicking the <img src="data:image/png;base64," style="width: 68px;">&nbsp;button next to the respective package.</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857;">We love this kind of feedback and hope you find this change useful, so keep the feedback coming!</span></p><p><span style="line-height: 1.42857; font-style: italic;">Happy Packaging!</span></p>
